  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering in the United States:\n\n1. Federal Statutes:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- Anti-Money Laundering Act of 2020\n- USA PATRIOT Act\n\n2. Key Federal Provisions:\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1956 - Laundering of monetary instruments\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1957 - Engaging in monetary transactions in property derived from specified unlawful activity\n\n3. State Laws:\n- Many states have their own money laundering statutes that complement federal laws\n- These often mirror federal provisions but can have specific state-level requirements\n\n4. International Regulations:\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- Various international treaties and agreements\n\nThese statutes generally:\n- Define money laundering\n- Establish reporting requirements\n- Mandate financial institution compliance\n- Prescribe criminal penalties\n- Provide mechanisms for asset forfeiture\n\nPenalties can include significant fines and imprisonment, depending on the specific circumstances and severity of the offense.\n\nFinancial institutions are required to implement comprehensive anti-money laundering (AML) compliance programs under these statutes.",
